1017,"Invalid syntax when using allowDiskUse:True through PyMongo

I got this problem when setting allowDiskUse to True, there are many similar questions about 'allowDiskUse' and none of them work in my case.
I use python 3.6.4 MongoDB 3.6.3 and pymongo 3.6.1

,WeakSet makes no sense. The path has no referers anymore so it gets deleted. It would just disapear from the set. I tried WeakKeyDictionary using the generated index as key and the path as value. But the View uses only the c++ part of the QModelIndex internally. PyQt forgets the generated QModelIndex and creates a new one when the View calls Model.data(). So the path drops from the WeakKeyDictionary too.

What I did now is store the user id as integer in the QModelIndex for roles and -1 for user. The stored user id + the index.row() then gives me all the info I need, luckily.","Embed Field: Invalid syntax when using allowDiskUse:True through PyMongo

I got this problem when setting allowDiskUse to True, there are many similar questions about 'allowDiskUse' and none of them work in my case.
I use python 3.6.4 MongoDB 3.6.3 and pymongo 3.6.1

column2: Answer: WeakSet makes no sense. The path has no referers anymore so it gets deleted. It would just disapear from the set. I tried WeakKeyDictionary using the generated index as key and the path as value. But the View uses only the c++ part of the QModelIndex internally. PyQt forgets the generated QModelIndex and creates a new one when the View calls Model.data(). So the path drops from the WeakKeyDictionary too.

We are facing a problem with this approach. If we have the entity user:
And we want to expose this entity as a resource, but we don't really know what parameters the client will use to search on this repository, so we'll end up with something like:

We will have to create a lot of methods in the user repository and conditionals to use them to give an answer back according to the client's query. And this problem will grow as the entity gets more fields.
I know that spring supports query by example but it won't work if we need to search by range of date for example.
Is there a way to take advantage of the Spring repositories even though we don't know what queries is our service receive?
